The paper deals with the problem of constructing a $k$-core in a graph, which is a common topic in graph theory and network analysis. The paper also mentions the computational complexity of the problem, which suggests that it may belong to the sub-categories of algorithms and complexity (cs.DS) or computational geometry (cs.CG). However, the focus of the paper is on the graph-theoretical aspects of the problem, such as the structural properties of sparse graphs and the minimum size of a vertex cover, which are more closely related to discrete mathematics (cs.DM) and graph theory (cs.GT). Additionally, the paper discusses the application of $k$-cores in modeling social networks, which falls under the sub-category of social and information networks (cs.SI).
